{
  "Nuclear power plants generate electricity through:": "",
  "Nuclear fission, where uranium-235 atoms are split, releasing heat to produce steam that drives turbines": "",
  "Combustion of uranium fuel pellets inside a conventional high-temperature furnace similar to a coal-fired boiler system": "",
  "Nuclear fusion reactions that combine hydrogen isotopes under extreme pressure to create helium and release thermal energy": "",
  "Exothermic chemical reactions between refined metallic compounds that generate enough sustained heat to boil water for steam": "",
  "Commercial nuclear power uses fission, where neutrons split U-235 atoms in a chain reaction that releases enormous energy as heat, which boils water to create steam that turns electricity-generating turbines.": "",
  "A major advantage of nuclear power over fossil fuels is that:": "",
  "Nuclear plants produce virtually no greenhouse gas emissions during operation": "",
  "Nuclear fuel is renewable": "",
  "Nuclear plants produce no waste at all": "",
  "Nuclear plants are cheaper to build than coal plants": "",
  "During operation, nuclear reactors produce electricity without burning fuel or emitting CO2, making nuclear power one of the lowest-carbon electricity sources, comparable to wind and solar on a lifecycle basis.": "",
  "The Chernobyl disaster (1986) was the worst nuclear accident because:": "",
  "A relatively minor and contained radioactive leak that was fully controlled within the reactor building without external release": "",
  "Structural damage limited exclusively to the outer reactor containment building shell with no compromise of the inner core systems": "",
  "An incident where absolutely no measurable radioactive contamination was released beyond the immediate boundaries of the plant site": "",
  "A reactor explosion and fire released massive amounts of radioactive material, contaminating large areas of Europe": "",
  "The Chernobyl explosion scattered radioactive material across Europe, forced permanent evacuation of a 30-km exclusion zone, caused thousands of thyroid cancer cases, and remains uninhabitable in some areas decades later.": "",
  "The Fukushima Daiichi accident (2011) was triggered by:": "",
  "A massive earthquake and tsunami that overwhelmed the plant's safety systems, causing three reactor meltdowns": "",
  "A series of deliberate human operator errors committed during a routine maintenance procedure that compromised all reactor cooling systems": "",
  "A coordinated terrorist attack on the facility that simultaneously disabled multiple independent safety and backup power generation systems": "",
  "Gradual deterioration of aging equipment and structural components that had not been properly maintained or replaced on the recommended schedule": "",
  "A magnitude 9.0 earthquake followed by a 14-meter tsunami knocked out Fukushima's backup cooling systems, leading to three reactor meltdowns, hydrogen explosions, and widespread radioactive contamination.": "",
  "The biggest unresolved challenge of nuclear power is:": "",
  "Sourcing and transporting sufficient volumes of cooling water from nearby rivers or ocean sources to maintain safe reactor operating temperatures": "",
  "Safely storing highly radioactive spent fuel that remains dangerous for thousands to hundreds of thousands of years": "",
  "Recruiting and training enough qualified nuclear engineers, technicians, and safety personnel to operate complex modern reactor facilities": "",
  "Generating enough total electrical output from nuclear fission to meet increasing baseload electricity demand in growing population centers": "",
  "No country has yet built a permanent repository for high-level nuclear waste; spent fuel rods remain radioactive for tens of thousands of years, requiring isolation from the biosphere far longer than any human institution has existed.": "",
  "Nuclear power currently provides approximately what percentage of global electricity?": "",
  "About 1%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 75%": "",
  "Nuclear energy supplies approximately 10% of global electricity from about 440 operating reactors in 32 countries, with France generating the highest share of its electricity (about 70%) from nuclear power.": "",
  "Uranium mining can contaminate the environment through:": "",
  "Radioactive tailings, radon gas release, groundwater contamination, and heavy metal pollution": "",
  "Exclusively minor noise pollution from surface-level equipment operations at mine sites without any chemical or radiological contamination": "",
  "Absolutely no documented or scientifically measurable environmental impacts of any kind associated with commercial uranium mining operations": "",
  "Only localized airborne dust particle production from earth-moving activities at the mine site without any toxic or radioactive component": "",
  "Uranium mining generates radioactive waste rock and tailings that can contaminate air with radon gas and pollute water with radioactive materials and heavy metals, particularly affecting indigenous communities near mine sites.": "",
  "The half-life of plutonium-239 is approximately 24,000 years, which means:": "",
  "The radioactive material completely decays into stable non-radioactive atoms within a single 24,000-year half-life period and becomes entirely safe": "",
  "After exactly 24,000 years the plutonium-239 becomes entirely safe for human handling and can be disposed of through conventional waste methods": "",
  "Half its radioactivity remains after 24,000 years, requiring secure storage for hundreds of thousands of years": "",
  "Plutonium-239 has been definitively shown to be non-radioactive and poses no significant radiation hazard during storage or handling procedures": "",
  "After one half-life of 24,000 years, half the plutonium-239 remains radioactive; approximately 10 half-lives (240,000 years) are needed for it to decay to safe levels, far exceeding human civilization's entire history.": "",
  "Nuclear fusion differs from fission in that fusion:": "",
  "Produces more radioactive waste than fission": "",
  "Is currently used in all commercial reactors": "",
  "Combines light atoms like hydrogen to form heavier atoms, potentially producing vast energy with minimal waste": "",
  "Splits heavy atoms apart": "",
  "Fusion, the process powering the sun, combines hydrogen isotopes to form helium with enormous energy release and minimal radioactive waste, but achieving sustained controlled fusion on Earth remains a major scientific challenge.": "",
  "France generates about 70% of its electricity from nuclear power, demonstrating that:": "",
  "Nuclear power is only viable in small quantities": "",
  "A nation can rely heavily on nuclear energy for low-carbon electricity while maintaining grid reliability": "",
  "Nuclear power cannot provide reliable baseload electricity": "",
  "France has no environmental concerns about nuclear energy": "",
  "France's extensive nuclear fleet provides reliable, low-carbon baseload electricity and gives the country one of the lowest carbon intensities per kWh in Europe, though it still faces challenges with waste storage and aging reactors.": "",
  "What is nuclear fission?": "",
  "The combining of two light atomic nuclei": "",
  "The decay of carbon-14 in organic material": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy atomic nucleus into two or more lighter nuclei, releasing large amounts of energy": "",
  "The chemical burning of radioactive material": "",
  "Nuclear fission occurs when a neutron strikes a heavy nucleus like U-235, causing it to split into smaller nuclei while releasing energy and additional neutrons that sustain the chain reaction.": "",
  "What is radioactive half-life?": "",
  "The time it takes for radioactive material to become completely safe": "",
  "The time required for half of a radioactive substance to decay into a more stable form": "",
  "The halfway point in a nuclear reactor's operational life": "",
  "The time a nuclear plant operates before maintenance": "",
  "Radioactive half-life is a constant for each isotope; after each half-life period, exactly half the remaining radioactive atoms have decayed, meaning the material never truly reaches zero but becomes progressively less radioactive.": "",
  "What is a nuclear meltdown?": "",
  "The standard industrial process of chemically reprocessing and recycling used nuclear fuel rods to extract remaining fissile material for reuse": "",
  "A carefully planned and controlled shutdown procedure that safely brings a nuclear reactor from full power to a cold non-operating condition": "",
  "The routine and expected day-to-day operational behavior of a nuclear reactor running within its normal design parameters and safety margins": "",
  "The overheating and melting of a reactor's fuel rods due to failure of cooling systems, potentially releasing radiation": "",
  "A meltdown occurs when cooling systems fail, causing fuel rods to overheat and melt through their containment, potentially releasing radioactive material into the environment, as occurred at Chernobyl and Fukushima.": "",
  "What is spent nuclear fuel?": "",
  "Fuel that has been fully consumed with no remaining radioactivity": "",
  "Used fuel rods removed from a reactor that are still highly radioactive and contain fission products requiring long-term isolation": "",
  "Coal ash from a power plant": "",
  "Fresh uranium ready to be loaded into a reactor": "",
  "Spent fuel has been used in a reactor until it can no longer efficiently sustain fission, but it remains intensely radioactive due to fission products and must be carefully managed for thousands of years.": "",
  "What is nuclear proliferation?": "",
  "The spread of nuclear weapons capability or materials to nations or groups that do not currently possess them": "",
  "The increase in nuclear energy efficiency": "",
  "The growth of nuclear power plants worldwide": "",
  "The natural spread of radiation from a reactor": "",
  "Nuclear proliferation is a security concern because the same technology used to enrich uranium for reactor fuel can be further enriched for weapons, and plutonium from spent fuel can potentially be extracted for bombs.": "",
  "What is a chain reaction in nuclear physics?": "",
  "A sequence of cascading chemical explosions that propagate through connected fuel storage systems and amplify destructive energy with each detonation": "",
  "A self-sustaining sequence of fission events where neutrons released from one split atom trigger additional atoms to split": "",
  "A specialized water-cooling circulation system engineered to remove excess thermal energy from reactor components during normal power generation": "",
  "The physical interconnection of multiple nuclear power generating stations through a shared high-voltage electrical transmission distribution grid": "",
  "In a chain reaction, each fission event releases 2-3 neutrons that can split other U-235 atoms, creating a self-sustaining process controlled in reactors by absorbing excess neutrons with control rods.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "A type of nuclear weapon detonation process that occurs exclusively in military applications and has no relevance to civilian energy production": "",
  "The controversial practice of disposing radioactive nuclear waste materials by dumping sealed containers into deep ocean trenches for permanent storage": "",
  "The process of breaking apart heavy atomic nuclei like uranium or plutonium into smaller fragments to release the binding energy stored within them": "",
  "The combining of light atomic nuclei under extreme temperature and pressure to form heavier nuclei, releasing enormous energy": "",
  "Fusion powers the sun by combining hydrogen nuclei into helium at temperatures exceeding 100 million degrees, releasing far more energy per unit mass than fission with minimal radioactive waste.": "",
  "What is an exclusion zone?": "",
  "An area surrounding a nuclear accident site from which people are permanently evacuated due to dangerous radiation levels": "",
  "A safety zone around a construction site": "",
  "A restricted area within a nuclear power plant during normal operations": "",
  "A no-fishing zone in the ocean": "",
  "Exclusion zones like the 30-km zone around Chernobyl are areas deemed too contaminated for human habitation, often for decades or longer, though wildlife has paradoxically thrived in the absence of human activity.": "",
  "What is enrichment in the context of nuclear fuel?": "",
  "The procedure of removing spent fuel rod assemblies from the reactor core and placing them in cooling water pools after they finish generating power": "",
  "The practice of supplementing nuclear fuel pellets with essential vitamin and mineral additives to enhance the efficiency of the fission chain reaction": "",
  "The initial step of physically excavating uranium ore from underground or open-pit mine sites before it undergoes any chemical processing or refinement": "",
  "The process of increasing the concentration of fissile U-235 in uranium from its natural 0.7% to the 3-5% needed for reactor fuel": "",
  "Natural uranium contains only 0.7% fissile U-235, so enrichment increases this percentage to 3-5% for reactor use through processes like gas centrifugation; weapons-grade uranium requires enrichment above 90%.": "",
  "What is a cooling pond (spent fuel pool)?": "",
  "A recreational swimming pool facility constructed at a nuclear power plant campus specifically for the physical fitness and relaxation of plant workers": "",
  "An aquaculture fish farming pond located adjacent to a nuclear facility that uses warm discharge water to accelerate commercial fish growth rates": "",
  "A natural freshwater lake situated near a nuclear power station that receives and dissipates waste thermal energy from the reactor steam condensing system": "",
  "A deep, water-filled basin where highly radioactive spent fuel rods are stored underwater for cooling and radiation shielding after removal from the reactor": "",
  "Spent fuel pools provide water that both absorbs the intense heat from radioactive decay in recently removed fuel rods and shields workers from radiation, typically holding spent fuel for 5-10 years before dry cask storage.": "",
  "After the Fukushima disaster, Germany decided to phase out all its nuclear power plants by 2022. Meanwhile, France continues to rely on nuclear for 70% of its electricity. This policy difference illustrates that:": "",
  "Nations weigh the risks and benefits of nuclear energy differently based on their energy needs, geography, public opinion, and available alternatives": "",
  "One nation made the objectively correct decision while the other nation made a clearly wrong choice about nuclear energy policy direction and investment": "",
  "Both Germany and France have completely phased out all nuclear electricity generation and transitioned entirely to renewable energy sources by now": "",
  "Nuclear energy technology presents absolutely identical safety risks, economic costs, and environmental consequences in every country regardless of context": "",
  "Nuclear energy policy reflects different national risk assessments: Germany prioritized accident risk and public concern, while France emphasized low-carbon energy security, showing how the same technology faces different societal evaluations.": "",
  "The US government selected Yucca Mountain in Nevada as a permanent nuclear waste repository, but the project was halted due to political opposition. Currently, spent fuel is stored at individual reactor sites across the country. This situation creates risk because:": "",
  "Temporary storage at 70+ dispersed sites creates more security vulnerabilities and accident risks than a single engineered geological repository": "",
  "Political opposition is irrelevant to nuclear safety": "",
  "Spent fuel at reactor sites is completely safe indefinitely": "",
  "There is no spent fuel at US reactor sites": "",
  "Storing radioactive waste at dozens of sites increases overall risk compared to centralized storage in a purpose-built geological repository, yet no community wants to host such a facility, creating a political impasse.": "",
  "A country considering building its first nuclear power plant must evaluate the full lifecycle costs. Beyond construction, these costs include:": "",
  "There are absolutely no additional financial costs or obligations of any kind after the initial construction of a nuclear power plant is completed": "",
  "The only significant ongoing expense is the periodic purchase of processed uranium fuel assemblies needed to sustain the nuclear fission chain reaction": "",
  "Insurance premiums against potential nuclear accidents represent the sole meaningful operational cost beyond the initial construction capital expenditure": "",
  "Uranium mining and enrichment, decades of operation and maintenance, eventual decommissioning, and centuries of waste management": "",
  "Nuclear power's full lifecycle costs extend far beyond construction to include fuel processing, decades of operation, costly decommissioning when reactors retire, and waste storage for thousands of years, making it one of the most expensive electricity sources.": "",
  "Proponents of small modular reactors (SMRs) argue they could make nuclear energy safer and more accessible because:": "",
  "Small modular reactor technology has already been extensively deployed and commercially operated for multiple decades across dozens of countries worldwide": "",
  "Small modular reactors operate through entirely non-nuclear chemical energy conversion processes that require no fissile uranium or plutonium fuel material": "",
  "Their smaller size allows factory manufacturing, passive safety features that work without power, and lower upfront costs": "",
  "Small modular reactor designs have completely eliminated all radioactive waste production through advanced fuel recycling and neutron capture technology": "",
  "SMRs are designed with passive safety systems that can cool the reactor without electricity or human intervention, reducing meltdown risk, and their smaller size makes them potentially affordable for smaller grids.": "",
  "The Chernobyl exclusion zone, while uninhabitable for humans, has become a thriving wildlife refuge with wolves, bison, and wild horses. This paradox demonstrates that:": "",
  "All animal species are completely immune to ionizing radiation exposure and suffer absolutely no biological harm from living in contaminated environments": "",
  "The removal of human activity can benefit wildlife more than the presence of radiation harms it, though individual animals may still suffer radiation effects": "",
  "All radioactive contamination from the 1986 Chernobyl disaster has completely dissipated and the exclusion zone is now safe for permanent human habitation": "",
  "Chronic exposure to elevated levels of ionizing radiation is actually beneficial for wildlife health and promotes increased reproduction and genetic fitness": "",
  "While individual organisms at Chernobyl show radiation damage, the absence of human hunting, farming, and development has allowed wildlife populations to thrive, illustrating that human activity can be more harmful to ecosystems than radiation.": "",
  "Japan's Fukushima disaster released radioactive water into the Pacific Ocean. Trace levels of Fukushima-derived cesium have been detected in fish off the US West Coast, though at levels far below safety limits. This raises the issue of:": "",
  "How nuclear accidents can have transboundary effects spanning entire oceans, even when contamination levels are too low to pose health risks": "",
  "The urgent practical necessity of immediately halting all commercial and recreational fishing activities throughout the entire Pacific Ocean basin": "",
  "A well-established scientific principle that radioactive contamination cannot physically travel through or be transported by ocean water currents": "",
  "Conclusive scientific evidence that all fish species harvested from anywhere in the Pacific Ocean are now permanently unsafe for human consumption": "",
  "Nuclear contamination can spread across vast distances through ocean currents, demonstrating that nuclear accidents have global dimensions even when diluted contamination poses minimal health risk.": "",
  "Climate scientists argue that meeting Paris Agreement targets may require maintaining or expanding nuclear power. Environmentalists opposed to nuclear counter that renewables can fill the gap. This debate centers on:": "",
  "A widely accepted scientific finding that nuclear energy production generates significantly more carbon dioxide emissions per kilowatt-hour than coal plants": "",
  "Whether the risks of nuclear power (accidents, waste, proliferation) are acceptable trade-offs for its reliable, low-carbon electricity in the fight against climate change": "",
  "Whether anthropogenic climate change is actually occurring or is simply a natural cyclical variation in global temperature patterns over geological timescales": "",
  "Whether commercially available photovoltaic solar panel systems can generate any measurable electrical output during nighttime hours without direct sunlight": "",
  "The nuclear-climate debate weighs nuclear's reliable, low-carbon generation against its accident risks, waste challenges, and costs, compared to the intermittency challenges but declining costs of solar and wind.": "",
  "Indigenous communities near uranium mines in the American Southwest and Australia have experienced elevated cancer rates and water contamination. This represents:": "",
  "A coincidental statistical correlation with no established causal connection between uranium mining activities and observed community health outcomes": "",
  "Definitive epidemiological proof that commercial uranium mining operations produce absolutely no adverse health effects in surrounding residential populations": "",
  "Clear evidence that all mineral extraction mining operations provide substantial direct economic benefits to every local community in the surrounding area": "",
  "An environmental justice issue where the health costs of nuclear fuel production are disproportionately borne by marginalized communities": "",
  "Uranium mining has historically been concentrated near indigenous communities who bear the health burdens of radioactive contamination while receiving few benefits, representing a clear environmental justice violation.": "",
  "A nuclear power plant operates for 40 years and then must be decommissioned. The decommissioning process typically takes 20-60 years and can cost billions. A policy maker considering nuclear must recognize that:": "",
  "Nuclear power generating facilities never reach the end of their operational lifespan and therefore never require decommissioning or dismantlement procedures": "",
  "The complete process of decommissioning a retired nuclear power plant typically requires only a few working days and minimal specialized technical expertise": "",
  "The full cost of nuclear includes decades of decommissioning and perpetual waste management that must be funded throughout the plant's operating life": "",
  "Decommissioning retired nuclear facilities is completely free of cost and can be accomplished instantly with no ongoing waste management financial obligations": "",
  "Nuclear economics must account for the enormous end-of-life costs including careful dismantling of radioactive structures, site remediation, and long-term waste management, which together can exceed original construction costs.": "",
